3. In `loadConversationGraphContext`, when `inheritedEntityIds` is non-empty, after loading the normal extraction_relation rows, load the inherited entities directly if they haven't already appeared:
   ```typescript
   if (options?.inheritedEntityIds && options.inheritedEntityIds.length > 0 && items.length < 5) {
     for (const entityRecord of options.inheritedEntityIds) {
       const entityId = entityRecord.id as string;
       if (seen.has(entityId)) continue;
       const entityTable = entityRecord.tb;
       if (!isExtractableKind(entityTable)) continue;
       const entityText = await readEntityText(surreal, entityRecord as GraphEntityRecord);
       if (!entityText) continue;
       // Use a synthetic confidence of 0.7 for inherited context
       items.push({
         id: entityRecord as GraphEntityRecord,
         kind: entityTable,
         text: entityText,
         confidence: 0.7,
         sourceMessage: entityRecord as unknown as RecordId<"message", string>, // synthetic
       });
       seen.add(entityId);
     }
   }
   ```

   Note: The `sourceMessage` field on `ExtractionGraphContextRow` is used only for display/provenance in the system prompt, not for graph writes. Using the entity record itself as a synthetic stand-in is acceptable here and clearly annotated. The confidence of 0.7 signals "inherited context, not directly extracted" without overwhelming the context window with max-confidence signals.

Also modify `buildChatContext` in `chat/context.ts` to accept the inherited entity IDs and pass them to `listConversationEntities`, so the orchestrator system prompt also shows inherited entities under "Entities already extracted from this conversation." This improves the orchestrator's initial awareness on the first message of a branch.

The `listConversationEntities` query in `graph/queries.ts` would need a parallel query that fetches the inherited entity records directly (by RecordId) and merges them, similar to what's described for `loadConversationGraphContext`.

---

### Layer 4 — Sidebar: branch nesting

**Files:**
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/shared/contracts.ts`
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/server/workspace/conversation-sidebar.ts`

#### 4a. Contract changes in `contracts.ts`

Add `branches` to `ConversationSidebarItem`:

```typescript
export type ConversationSidebarItem = {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  updatedAt: string;
  branches?: ConversationSidebarItem[];  // optional; undefined when no branches
  parentId?: string;  // set on branch items so UI can track lineage
};
```

`branches` is `undefined` when empty (never `null` per AGENTS.md). The UI renders a nested list only when `branches` is present and non-empty.

Add the new response type for the branch endpoint:

```typescript
export type BranchConversationRequest = {
  contextEntityIds?: string[];
};

export type BranchConversationResponse = {
  conversationId: string;
  parentConversationId: string;
};
```

#### 4b. Sidebar builder changes in `conversation-sidebar.ts`

The current `buildWorkspaceConversationSidebar` function loads conversations flat and groups by project. It needs to additionally:

1. Load all `branched_from` edges for the workspace's conversations:
   ```typescript
   type BranchedFromRow = {
     in: RecordId<"conversation", string>;  // branch
     out: RecordId<"conversation", string>; // parent
   };

   const [branchEdges] = await surreal.query<[BranchedFromRow[]]>(
     "SELECT `in`, out FROM branched_from WHERE `in` IN $conversations;",
     { conversations: conversationIds },
   ).collect<[BranchedFromRow[]]>();
   ```

2. Build a `parentMap: Map<string, string>` (childId → parentId) and a `childrenMap: Map<string, string[]>` (parentId → childIds[]).

3. During the `groupConversationsByProject` step, only include root conversations (those with no parent in `parentMap`) as top-level items. Their branches are attached as the `branches` field.

4. The `groupConversationsByProject` pure function signature changes to accept the branch relationship:

   ```typescript
   export type ConversationGroupInput = {
     id: string;
     title?: string;
     updatedAt: string;
     touchedBy: Array<{ projectId: string; entityCount: number }>;
     parentId?: string;   // set for branch conversations
   };
   ```

   In the grouping loop, conversations with `parentId` set are skipped (they are not placed at the top level). After groups are built, a second pass attaches branches to their parent items.

5. The `ConversationSidebarItem` construction gains a `branches` field populated by recursive lookup:

   ```typescript
   function attachBranches(
     item: ConversationSidebarItem,
     childrenMap: Map<string, ConversationSidebarItem[]>,
   ): ConversationSidebarItem {
     const children = childrenMap.get(item.id);
     if (!children || children.length === 0) return item;
     return {
       ...item,
       branches: children.map((child) => attachBranches(child, childrenMap)),
     };
   }
   ```

   This is a simple recursive helper. Since conversation nesting is shallow in practice (users rarely create branch-of-branch chains more than 2-3 deep), there is no stack overflow risk.

---

### Layer 5 — New API route: `POST /api/workspaces/:workspaceId/conversations/:parentId/branch`

**File:** `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/server/runtime/start-server.ts`

Register the new route in `start-server.ts`:

```typescript
import { createBranchConversationHandler } from "../chat/branch-conversation";

// ... in startServer():
const branchConversationHandler = createBranchConversationHandler(deps);

// In routes object:
"/api/workspaces/:workspaceId/conversations/:parentId/branch": {
  POST: withRequestLogging(
    "POST /api/workspaces/:workspaceId/conversations/:parentId/branch",
    "POST",
    (request) =>
      branchConversationHandler(
        request.params.workspaceId,
        request.params.parentId,
        request,
      ),
  ),
},
```

Also update the `createWorkspaceRouteHandlers` return type in `workspace-routes.ts` to expose the handler, OR keep it as a standalone handler factory (matching the pattern of `createWorkItemAcceptHandler`). The standalone pattern is cleaner since it avoids modifying the existing workspace handler creation function.

---

### Layer 6 — UI changes in `chat-page.tsx`

**File:** `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/client/routes/chat-page.tsx`

#### 6a. State additions

```typescript
const [branchingFromId, setBranchingFromId] = useState<string | undefined>();
```

No additional state is needed for the branch navigation — when a branch is created, the UI calls `loadConversation(workspace.id, newConversationId)` which transitions to the branch. The `backendConversationId` and `activeConversationId` update normally.

#### 6b. Branch action function

```typescript
async function onBranchConversation() {
  if (!workspace || !activeConversationId || isLoading) return;

  setBranchingFromId(activeConversationId);
  try {
    const response = await fetch(
      `/api/workspaces/${encodeURIComponent(workspace.id)}/conversations/${encodeURIComponent(activeConversationId)}/branch`,
      {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify({ contextEntityIds: [] }), // empty = auto from parent
      },
    );

    if (!response.ok) {
      const body = await response.text();
      setErrorMessage(body);
      return;
    }

    const payload = (await response.json()) as BranchConversationResponse;
    await loadConversation(workspace.id, payload.conversationId);
    await refreshSidebar(workspace.id);
  } catch (error) {
    setErrorMessage(error instanceof Error ? error.message : "branch failed");
  } finally {
    setBranchingFromId(undefined);
  }
}
```

#### 6c. Branch button in the chat header

In the JSX, add a Branch button to the `SessionMessagesHeader` area:

```tsx
<SessionMessagesHeader>
  <div className="reachat-header">
    Workspace Chat + Extraction
    {activeConversationId && workspace?.onboardingState === "complete" ? (
      <button
        type="button"
        className="branch-conversation-btn"
        onClick={() => void onBranchConversation()}
        disabled={isLoading || branchingFromId !== undefined}
      >
        {branchingFromId ? "Branching..." : "Branch"}
      </button>
    ) : undefined}
  </div>
</SessionMessagesHeader>
```

The button is only shown when onboarding is complete (no branching during onboarding) and a conversation is active.

#### 6d. Recursive sidebar rendering

The sidebar rendering of `ConversationSidebarItem` needs to handle `branches`. Extract a small component or a render function:

```tsx
function renderConversationItem(
  conv: ConversationSidebarItem,
  activeConversationId: string | undefined,
  onSelect: (id: string) => void,
  isLoading: boolean,
  depth: number = 0,
): React.ReactNode {
  return (
    <li key={conv.id} style={{ paddingLeft: depth * 12 }}>
      <button
        type="button"
        className={`sidebar-conversation-item${conv.id === activeConversationId ? " sidebar-conversation-item--active" : ""}${depth > 0 ? " sidebar-conversation-item--branch" : ""}`}
        onClick={() => onSelect(conv.id)}
        disabled={isLoading}
      >
        {depth > 0 ? "↳ " : ""}{conv.title}
      </button>
      {conv.branches && conv.branches.length > 0 ? (
        <ul className="sidebar-conversation-list">
          {conv.branches.map((branch) =>
            renderConversationItem(branch, activeConversationId, onSelect, isLoading, depth + 1)
          )}
        </ul>
      ) : undefined}
    </li>
  );
}
```

Replace the existing flat `<li>` rendering in `group.conversations.map(...)` and `sidebar.unlinked.map(...)` with calls to `renderConversationItem(conv, activeConversationId, onSelectConversation, isLoading)`.

---

### Sequencing and Dependencies

The steps must be implemented in this order to avoid breaking the running system:

1. **Schema first** — add the `branched_from` table definition. This is purely additive; nothing existing reads or writes this table yet.

2. **Contracts** — add `BranchConversationRequest`, `BranchConversationResponse`, and extend `ConversationSidebarItem` with the optional `branches` and `parentId` fields. These are backward compatible: existing code receives `ConversationSidebarItem` objects without `branches` and will continue working.

3. **Branch creation route** — implement `chat/branch-conversation.ts` and register the route in `start-server.ts`. This introduces the new endpoint.

4. **Sidebar nesting** — modify `conversation-sidebar.ts` to query `branched_from` edges and build the nested structure. The sidebar response changes shape but is backward compatible (new optional fields).

5. **Context inheritance** — modify `context-loaders.ts` and `chat-processor.ts` to detect and inject inherited context. This only fires for branch conversations; all existing conversations have no `branched_from` edges and are unaffected.

6. **UI** — add the Branch button, the `onBranchConversation` function, and recursive sidebar rendering.

---

### Edge Cases and Potential Issues

**Branch of a branch.** The schema and sidebar tree builder both handle recursive nesting naturally. The `attachBranches` recursive function traverses the `childrenMap` regardless of depth.

**Orphaned branch (parent deleted).** This codebase does not have conversation deletion, so this is not a current concern.

**Context entity IDs that no longer exist.** When loading inherited context in `loadConversationGraphContext`, if `readEntityText` returns `undefined` for an inherited entity, it is silently skipped. This matches the same pattern in the existing non-inherited path (line 98-100 of `context-loaders.ts`).

**The `context_entities[*]` sub-field in SCHEMAFULL mode.** Per AGENTS.md and the SurrealDB docs, `DEFINE FIELD context_entities[*] ON branched_from TYPE record` is required. Without it, writes to `context_entities` will silently drop the array elements in SCHEMAFULL mode. This must be in the schema before any branch is created.

**`RELATE` direction for `branched_from`.** SurrealDB `RELATE in->edge->out` — the `in` field holds the left side of the arrow. For the statement `RELATE branchRecord, edgeRecord, parentRecord`, `branchRecord` is the new branch (subject), `parentRecord` is the parent it was branched from. This means "branch is branched_from parent." The sidebar query `SELECT \`in\`, out FROM branched_from WHERE \`in\` IN $conversations` returns child conversations (the branches themselves) and their parents (`out`). To find children of a parent, query `WHERE out = $parentId`. This is consistent with the index definition `branched_from_out` on the `out` field.

**Auto-context selection when no `contextEntityIds` passed.** The route calls `loadConversationGraphContext(deps.surreal, parentConversationId, 30)` — note this uses the parent ID, not the new branch ID. The 30-entity limit keeps the context manageable and matches the extraction history window.

**`title_source` for branch conversations.** The branch title is set as `title_source: "message"` (initial default). This means `maybeUpgradeConversationTitle` will upgrade it after enough entities are extracted from the branch — the same behavior as a freshly created conversation. No special handling needed.

---

### What is NOT in scope

- Merging branches back into parents (not in the acceptance criteria)
- Displaying branch context entities as a separate UI panel (the `context_entities` on the edge are used for extraction bias only, not surfaced in the UI in this phase)
- Any changes to the extraction pipeline beyond the `loadConversationGraphContext` modification and the `chat-processor.ts` branch detection query

---

### Critical Files for Implementation

- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/schema/surreal-schema.surql` - Add `branched_from` TYPE RELATION table with all required SCHEMAFULL field declarations
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/server/extraction/context-loaders.ts` - Modify `loadConversationGraphContext` to accept and inject inherited entity context for early branch turns
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/server/workspace/conversation-sidebar.ts` - Modify sidebar builder to query `branched_from` edges and nest branch conversations under their parents
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/shared/contracts.ts` - Add `BranchConversationRequest`, `BranchConversationResponse`, and extend `ConversationSidebarItem` with `branches` and `parentId`
- `/Users/marcus/conductor/workspaces/brain/boston/app/src/client/routes/chat-page.tsx` - Add Branch button, `onBranchConversation` handler, and recursive sidebar rendering of nested branch items

